---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Case Study: Integrative Maturity | Diogo Soares">
  <article class="py-16">
    <div class="section-container">
      
      {/* Header */}
      <header class="mb-16 max-w-4xl">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
          <a href="/" class="text-text-muted hover:text-accent transition-colors text-sm flex items-center gap-2">
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="m12 19-7-7 7-7"/><path d="M19 12H5"/></svg>
            <span>Back</span>
          </a>
        </div>
        
        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 mb-6">
          <span class="badge">Product Strategy</span>
          <span class="badge">Anthropology</span>
          <span class="badge">Chatbots</span>
          <span class="badge">Leadership</span>
        </div>
        
        <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-display text-text mb-6 leading-tight">
          Integrative Maturity in Digital Products
        </h1>
        
        <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
          How anthropology and strategic management transform chatbots and high-performance teams.
        </p>
      </header>

      {/* Video Content - Replacing Embed with Link for reliability */}
      <section class="mb-16">
        <a 
          href="https://youtu.be/Db9J4zjdcjU?si=JBheDpHiHdP5oAjS" 
          target="_blank" 
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="group relative block aspect-video rounded-2xl overflow-hidden bg-surface-subtle shadow-card"
        >
          <img 
            src="/images/case-study-thumbnail.jpg" 
            alt="Watch video: Integrative Maturity" 
            class="w-full h-full object-cover group-hover:scale-105 transition-transform duration-500"
          />
          <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-text/30 flex items-center justify-center group-hover:bg-text/20 transition-all">
            <div class="w-20 h-20 rounded-full bg-accent text-white flex items-center justify-center shadow-2xl group-hover:scale-110 transition-transform">
              <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="currentColor"><path d="M8 5v14l11-7z"/></svg>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="absolute bottom-4 left-4 bg-black/60 backdrop-blur-md text-white text-xs px-3 py-1.5 rounded-lg border border-white/10">
            Watch on YouTube
          </div>
        </a>
      </section>

      {/* Content */}
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        
        {/* The Context */}
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-display text-text mb-6">The Context</h2>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
            In digital product development, especially in conversational interfaces (Chatbots) and Product team management, there's a natural tendency to view evolution as a straight line — a ladder to be climbed.
          </p>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
            In this case study, I propose a <strong class="text-text">paradigm shift</strong>: the transition from the linear model to the integrative model (Bricolage). This approach reflects my philosophy as a Group Product Manager (GPM), where technology is not just code, but a <strong class="text-text">complex cultural system</strong>.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* The Concept */}
        <section class="mb-12 p-8 bg-surface-subtle rounded-2xl border border-border">
          <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-display text-text mb-6">The Concept: From Triangle to Patchwork Quilt</h2>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
            Traditionally, product or professional maturity is viewed as a <strong class="text-text">Triangle</strong>: a wide base that narrows to the top, suggesting that success is just climbing steps (Junior → Senior, or MVP → Final Product).
          </p>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
            My approach challenges this view by adopting the concept of <strong class="text-accent">Bricolage</strong> (inspired by Claude Lévi-Strauss). Here, excellence is not about discarding the past to climb a step, but about weaving together disparate experiences, tools, and features into a cohesive and functional <strong class="text-text">"Patchwork Quilt"</strong>.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* Application */}
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-display text-text mb-8">Application on Two Fronts</h2>
          
          {/* Front 1 */}
          <div class="mb-10">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-accent mb-4 flex items-center gap-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-accent/10 flex items-center justify-center text-sm font-bold">1</span>
              Product Strategy (Chatbots)
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
              An immature chatbot is often designed as a simple <strong class="text-text">Decision Tree</strong>: rigid, binary, and limited.
            </p>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Under my management, product evolution follows the logic of a <strong class="text-accent">"Realm Map"</strong>:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-4 text-text-secondary">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-accent mt-1">▸</span>
                <span><strong class="text-text">Interconnected Territories:</strong> Users don't just follow a linear path; they explore an ecosystem. The bot can navigate between support questions, complex transactions, and discovery without losing context.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-accent mt-1">▸</span>
                <span><strong class="text-text">Legacy Integration:</strong> Instead of rewriting everything from scratch, we use bricolage logic to integrate legacy systems and new automations, creating a fluid experience for the end user.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          {/* Front 2 */}
          <div>
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-accent mb-4 flex items-center gap-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-accent/10 flex items-center justify-center text-sm font-bold">2</span>
              Team Leadership (Team Building)
            </h3>
            <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
              As a PM leader, I apply <strong class="text-accent">"Integrative Maturity"</strong> to build resilient teams.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-4 text-text-secondary">
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-accent mt-1">▸</span>
                <span><strong class="text-text">Valuing Trajectories:</strong> When hiring and developing talent, I look beyond technology hard skills. A professional who came from customer service, design, or humanities brings unique "patches" to the team's quilt.</span>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-accent mt-1">▸</span>
                <span><strong class="text-text">Creative Problem-Solving:</strong> Teams formed with this approach don't just look for the "right tool" in the manual; they examine available resources and create innovative solutions through recombining ideas.</span>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </section>

        {/* Differentiator */}
        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-display text-text mb-6">The Differentiator: Social Sciences Applied to Technology</h2>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            My background in <strong class="text-accent">Social Sciences and Anthropology (USP)</strong> is the foundation of this method. While the market often focuses excessively on isolated metrics, my approach differentiates by:
          </p>
          <div class="grid gap-4">
            <div class="p-5 bg-surface-elevated rounded-xl border border-border">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-text mb-2">Systemic Analysis</h4>
              <p class="text-text-secondary text-sm">Understanding the product as a cultural artifact embedded in the user's life, not just as software.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="p-5 bg-surface-elevated rounded-xl border border-border">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-text mb-2">Deep Product Discovery</h4>
              <p class="text-text-secondary text-sm">Using ethnographic methods to understand users' real pain points, going beyond what quantitative data shows.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="p-5 bg-surface-elevated rounded-xl border border-border">
              <h4 class="font-bold text-text mb-2">Humanized Management</h4>
              <p class="text-text-secondary text-sm">Leading with the understanding that team maturity is not numerical, but relational.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        {/* Conclusion */}
        <section class="mb-12 p-8 bg-accent/5 rounded-2xl border border-accent/20">
          <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-display text-text mb-6">Conclusion</h2>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
            This case study illustrates that true innovation in digital products doesn't happen just with new technologies, but with <strong class="text-text">new ways of organizing thought</strong>.
          </p>
          <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
            By replacing linear climbing with integrative construction, I deliver <strong class="text-accent">more robust products</strong> and develop <strong class="text-accent">more autonomous and creative teams</strong>.
          </p>
        </section>

        {/* Footer Note */}
        <footer class="pt-8 border-t border-border">
          <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">
            This case study is based on software development methodologies and structural anthropology concepts, reflecting my practical experience in product leadership.
          </p>
        </footer>

      </div>

      {/* CTA */}
      <div class="mt-20 text-center">
        <a href="/#contact" class="btn-accent text-lg px-8 py-4">
          <span>Let's Talk</span>
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M5 12h14"/><path d="m12 5 7 7-7 7"/></svg>
        </a>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>
